post_text:
Lincoln Middle School;
Yearbooks, diplomas, tassels, awards and PTA Gift
Good afternoon, Lincoln Middle School is scheduled for this Thursday, July, 23rd to have all 8th-grade students to pick up their diploma, tassel, yearbook, PTA gift, and some students will also receive certain awards. In addition, Black board connect calls have been sent out regarding the time schedules. Due to covid19 the students will have to wear a mask and keep the social distance to a 6ft. minimum.
Only Lincoln Middle School students will permitted on the blacktops on Kearny Avenue. Please note, will be starting at 8:00 instead of 9:00!!!

Good afternoon, Lincoln Middle School is scheduled for this Thursday, July, 23rd to have all 8th-grade students to pick up their diploma, tassel, yearbook, PTA gift, and some students will also receive certain awards. In addition, Black board connect calls have been sent out regarding the time schedules. Due to covid19 the students will have to wear a mask and keep the social distance to a 6ft. minimum.
Only Lincoln Middle School students will permitted on the blacktops on Kearny Avenue. Please note, will be starting at 8:00 instead of 9:00!!!

post_text: The Kearny School District is pleased to announce that free meals will continue to be available throughout the summer for ALL school-aged children, aged 18 and under who are residents of KEARNY. Grab & Go breakfast and lunch for 3 days will be distributed at the King St. entrance of Kearny HS every Monday, between 8:30 am and 12:00 pm., and 2 days of Grab & Go breakfast and lunch will be distributed on Thursdays. Food distribution will continue through Sept. 4th.

post_text: PART 2 (more pictures!) Garfield School Pre-K3 teacher Mrs. Ormaza: "I am very thankful for having the chance to see my little ones before the end of the year and let them know how proud I am of them and how much I’ve missed them! I could not be more grateful for all of the support that I’ve received from parents who, despite all the unforeseen obstacles, have helped make this a wonderful year. Thank you for being part of our Pre-k3 family. You will always have a special place in heart! Have a safe and fun summer!"

post_text: In Mrs. O’Grady’s class from Washington School they call themselves a family and their room is their home. The sudden separation was hard on them, but they still managed to have a whole lot of fun! Mrs. O’Grady learned so many ways to be a better teacher and her students surprised her with their creativity and dedication from a distance. She is so incredibly grateful to the @keepskidslearning program for helping her supply her students with some fun arts and crafts materials to keep them engaged and motivated this summer. She will miss them, but their memories will last a lifetime! (or accessed on their memory Padlet 🤪🤣) 😍🎉

post_text:
Congratulations to our Roosevelt School Students of the Month for June! This month we focused on the Pillar of Character, Fairness.

Fairness means playing by the rules, taking turns and sharing, being open-minded, listening to others, not taking advantage of or blaming others, and treating all people equally.

Your teachers recognized this character trait in each of you!
Students, if you are able to, share a picture below of you with your certificate! Keep up the great work 😁

Lincoln Middle School:
I want to thank our staff in the district. There is too much gratitude and too many specific “givers” and “doers” to list them all. What I can, without reservation, tell you is the staff of our district care deeply about your children, you as families, and our community. I would also like sincerely thank our parents, the community and Kearny Police Department for our celebrations of our 8th graders.
Lincoln Middle School community, your leadership, care, and good heart have shown through during this difficult and trying time. Thank you for being a beacon of positivity and purpose in a time where many are uncertain.
Thank you,
LMS

I would also like sincerely thank our parents, the community and Kearny Police Department for our celebrations of our 8th graders.
Lincoln Middle School community, your leadership, care, and good heart have shown through during this difficult and trying time. Thank you for being a beacon of positivity and purpose in a time where many are uncertain.
Thank you,
LMS

Your teachers recognized this character trait in each of you!
Students, if you are able to, share a picture below of you with your certificate! Keep up the great work 😁

post_text:
Lincoln Middle School:
During Mrs. Hemphill's weekly Google Meet, the students were introduced to the app, Alamry, that students can use to help them wake up. The app, "Takes wake up alarms to another level," by having users take a picture, shake the phone, solve a math problem or scan a QR/barcode to turn the alarm off. This week's special guest was, Miss Glenn. The students and administrators played a game and had to answer questions to see who they knew best. After a tight game, Mr. Hempel won against Mr. Moyano 10-8.
Which teacher had a pet duck?
Which teacher has never had a peanut butter and jelly sandwich?
Which teacher started her teacher career at Franklin School?
Thank you Mrs. Hemphill!!!

post_text:
Kindergarten Butterfly Project at Franklin School

Mrs. Janz spearheaded the caterpillars-to-butterfly project, which began its journey on April 13th. She shared their growth through videos and pictures with every Kindergarten class at Franklin School with the help of her 2 beautiful daugthers. The kindergarten students voted on name suggestions and read books about the butterfly life cycle and animal adaptations. The students recorded their observations of the this life cylce and are working on their final life cycle projects this week! The butterflies were released at the park today. This project was a labor of love and had special personal and professional significance to Mrs. Janz. Ms. Dyl and Miss Kerr enoyed the experience virutally with some very exicted students!

post_text: Schuyler School - Every Friday during Ms. Esparra's distance learning experience, her class goes on a virtual field trip. The students love it since it offers them a time to see each other and do something fun together while still learning. With schools being closed until June, a lot of the students have expressed how sad they are. So today (with the help of the students’ amazing parents) Ms. Esparra surprised each student with a goody bag. When she returned home, they met on Zoom for their weekly check in. During their meeting, she told the students that she had one more surprise. Next week they will be going to Walt Disney World’s Magic Kingdom (virtually, of course). The students will join her next Friday with their Disney gear and virtually tour Magic Kingdom while still making connections to our third grade curriculum in math and science.

post_text: Schuyler School - Taking a page from the "I Survived..." book series, Mrs. Cecere's 4th and 5th grade classes have been working on their very own version of "I Survived The Coronavirus Pandemic of 2020". The students recognize that they are a part of unprecedented times, and have been keeping an online journal to document this historic event. Their chapters range from when they first found out about the pandemic, the first week of remote learning, learning about community closures and the resulting impacts, and their feelings and outlook. The students have been working for weeks on this writing and have been doing an outstanding job. And of course, this will be something they will be able to hold on to forever since they have now personally experienced history.

post_text:
Since our administrators, supervisors, teachers, counselors, child study team members, and administrative assistants, are working remotely, our phone calls to parents may appear without a visible phone number. We hope you will recognize that calls from school personnel are important and you will consider answering calls from UNKNOWN. We apologize for any issues this may present.

Also, please check and, if necessary, update your contact information in the Genesis Parent Portal to reflect your current email and phone number to ensure school staff can reach you if necessary.

post_text:
DISTANCE LEARNING continues on Mon. March 23 through Friday, April 3, 2020.

KEARNY HIGH SCHOOL WILL BE THE DISTRICT BASE FOR ALL ESSENTIAL SERVICES. Needed technology repair and material pick-up is available between 8:30 am and 12:30 pm at the main entrance as needed. Someone will be there to assist. Check with your teacher or building administrator if you have any questions.

GRAB & GO breakfast & lunch is available for ALL Kearny residents 18 years of age and under. Pick-up at KHS King St. entrance between the hours of 8:30 & 12:00 noon, Monday thru Friday.

SPRING BREAK begins 4/4 and continues through 4/13. An available SNOW DAY is being used on Monday, April 13, 2020.

CLASSES RESUME Tuesday, April 14, 2020, but at this time, we cannot predict whether we will be returning to school or continuing DISTANCE LEARNING. We will update in accordance with the directives of the Governor's Office at that time

Stay safe and be well. #KearnyStrong #KearnyPride

post_text: Washington School often displays a strong sense of community and we decided to maintain our pride by creating a Virtual Spirit Week to show our connectedness although we are not with one another. Our goal today was to sport green in honor St. Patrick’s Day and bonus points if we showed off our first day of remote learning. We are so proud of our students and staff and how hard they’re working to still learn virtually and be united during this difficult time.

post_text: The Washington School preschoolers from Mrs. Gawronski Smyth’s class had a Creative Curriculum 'Wow' day at school! Former Kearny High School graduate and current Captain of the Baruch Men's Basketball team, George Smyth, Jr. stopped by to talk to the preschoolers about basketball as they have been investigating balls as part of their Ball Study. The experiences that our preschoolers had today allowed them to have a richer experience about how basketballs are used, how they move, and who uses them. It was truly a great day of meaningful learning at our school!
